Introduction to Data Science Assignment

MSc in Bioinformatics and Computational Biology
Helena Baptista (201406153), Joel Moreira (202008682)

  Our dataset was collected from the Real Hospital Portugês in Brasil. This dataset contains information about a large group of pediatric cardiology patients from a group of hospitals.

  The maingoal of this work is to classify NORMAL/ABNORMAL pediatric patients in cardiology.

This dataset contains various information about the patients:

  • Total of 17873 entries
  • Patient's ID#
  • Patient's Weight
  • Patient's Height
  • Patient's Body Mass Index
  • Patient's Date of Visit
  • Patient's Date of Birth
  • Patient's Age
  • Patient's Health Insurance
  • Patient's Pulse
  • Patient's Systolic Blood Pressure
  • Patient's Diastolic Blood Pressure
  • Patient's SBP/DBP
  • Presence or Absense of Pathology
  • Patient's Type of Second Heart Sound
  • Type of Heart Murmur
  • Patient's Cardiac Frequency
  • Patient's 1st History of Desease
  • Patient's 2nd History of Desease
  • Patient's Gender
  • Patient's 1st Motive for Consultation
  • Patient's 2nd Motive for Consultation

After visualising all the plots and data we proceeded to:

  • Standardize all the data - Diferent names are used to refer to the same thing (Example: "Masculino","masculino" and "M");
  • Correct variables that are int and were being consider "object";
  • Delete nonsense data such as negative ages.
  • Remove variables that contain too many missing values -- more than 50% missing values
  • Remove variables that won't be important for the model (health insurance variable, for example).

All of these were easily done with the help of Excel.

With the preprocessing done we had to start by importing our improved dataset back.

  All the variables were used in the model.

  We use adjusted R-squared to compare the goodness-of-fit for regression models that contain different numbers of independent variables. The R-squared varies between 0 and 1 (or %), having a better fit if closer to 1 (100).

  Our Linear-Regression Model presents a R-squared of 0.73 which is very good. However this model cannot be used convictely as our final model since the result of the same will be a number and that not indicate if a patient is "NORMAL" or "ANORMAL".

  We decided to use aglomerative hierarchical clustering to identify similiar groups of patients. With this method of cluster analysis, each cohort member starts as its own cluster. The 2 most similar clusters are merged and this new cluster replaces the former 2. The process continues until there is only 1 cluster containing all observations.

  Various algorithms are available for cluster analysis. For this study, we used Ward’s minimum variance method as the primary algorithm because it was already used in similar studies.

With the dendogram above we find out the optimal number of clusters to use.

We look for the largest distance that we can vertically without crossing any horizontal line.Then we count the number of lines on the diagram and determine the optimal number of clusters. In this case the optimal number of clusters is 3.

Support Vector Machines:

In case of non-linearly separable data, the simple SVM algorithm cannot be used. Rather, a modified version of SVM, called Kernel SVM, is used.

We used 3 different Kernels:

  • Polynomial
  • Gaussion
  • Signmoid

Conclusions

  After concluding the analysis steps using clusters, correlations and a multiple linear regression model, we used 3 different Supervised Machine Learning Models:

  • Decision Tree
  • SVM
  • Neural Network

These had different accuracy scores, and we can state that both SMV and NN worked well, but we think Neural Network was the best.

In the future, we could improve the data during the preprocessing by trying to impute data rather than deleting what didn't suit our parameters.
